The paper deals with the computational complexity of finding stable partitions in hedonic games, which is a topic in computational game theory (cs.GT). The use of additively separable preferences and dichotomous preferences suggests that the paper may also be relevant to research in artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also involves analyzing the complexity of decision problems, which is a topic in computational complexity theory (cs.DS). Finally, the paper deals with coalition formation, which is a topic in social networks and multi-agent systems (cs.SI).
